# BibTeX DOI-as-URL rule

## Rules

1. Every entry in a `.bib` file that contains a `doi` field **must** also include a `url` field of the form:

```
url = {https://doi.org/<doi-value>}
```

If an entry already has a `url` pointing somewhere other than the DOI resolver, **add** the DOI-based URL (keep the existing `url` only if it provides genuinely different content, e.g. an open-access preprint). If both would point to the same resource, prefer the DOI-based URL.

2. **Verify every DOI before writing it.** After adding or editing a `doi` field, fetch `https://doi.org/<doi-value>` (using the web fetch tool) to confirm it resolves to the expected publication. A DOI is verified when the fetched page matches the expected title/authors.

3. **If a DOI cannot be verified** (fetch fails, returns a 404, or resolves to a different publication), **remove the entire `.bib` entry** and delete every `\cite` or `\citep` reference to it in the corresponding `.tex` files. Do not leave dead citations. Inform the user which entry was removed and why.

## Rationale

DOI-based URLs are persistent and resolvable. Including them as clickable `url` fields ensures that compiled PDFs (via `hyperref`) link directly to the publication. Verifying existence prevents fabricated or mistyped DOIs from entering the bibliography.

## Example

```bibtex
@article{example2024,
  author = {Doe, Jane},
  title  = {An example article},
  journal = {Journal of Examples},
  year   = {2024},
  doi    = {10.1234/example.2024},
  url    = {https://doi.org/10.1234/example.2024}
}
```
